column168: A DRIVER FOR COAST GAS OF PALMETTO, FLORIDA WAS DRIVING NORTHBOUND ON US HWY 41 IN VENICE, FLORIDA WHEN A PICK UP PULLED OUT OF A SHOPPING CENTER PARKING LOT AND TURNED DIRECTLY IN FRONT OF HIM.  THE COAST GAS DRIVER BRAKED IMMEDIATELY AND HARD IN ORDER TO AVOID HITTING THE PICK UP.  THE BRAKING ACTION CAUSED THE TRUCK TO SLIDE AND THE LIQUID CARGO SHIFTED CAUSING THE TRUCK TO OVERTURN ON ITS SIDE.  THE PICK UP DID NOT STOP; HOWEVER, WITNESSES CONFIRMED THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT.  THERE WAS NO PRODUCT LOST DURING THE INCIDENT; HOWEVER, THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS OF PRODUCT FLARED OFF BY CONTROLLED MEANS PRIOR TO UP RIGHTING THE TRUCK.  THERE WAS NO EVACUATIONS BUT US HWY 41 WAS CLOSED FOR SEVERAL HOURS WHILE PRODUCT WAS PUMPED OFF THE OVERTURNED TRUCK.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE AT A WERNER ENTERPRISES DROP-YARD IN KENT, WASHINGTON, THE WERNER ENTERPRISES DRIVER DISCOVERED FREE PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER.  WERNER ENTERPRISES DISPATCHED NRC ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES OF SEATTLE, WASHINGTON TO PERFORM THE INVESTIGATION AND CLEANUP.  UPON INVESTIGATION, ONE LEAKING FIFTEEN GALLON PLASTIC DRUM WAS DISCOVERED IN THE REAR-QUARTER OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY FIFTEEN GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE ASPHALT.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A NAIL PUNCTURE TO THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  NRC ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES CLEANED THE AFFECTED ASPHALT AND DECONTAMINATED THE TRAILER.  NRC ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES GENERATED ONE, ONE HUNDRED AND NINETY-FIVE POUND DRUM OF WASTE, WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED TO BURLINGTON ENVIRONMENTAL IN KENT, WASHINGTON FOR DISPOSAL. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: TRAILER LOCATED AT FENCED AND LOCKED LOADING PAD HAD BEEN LOADED ON 06/02/04 FOR TRANSPORT ON 06/03/04.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1000 ON 06/03, WE DISCOVERED THE BOTTOM VALVE ON THE TRAILER WAS OPEN AND ITS CONTENTS HAD BEGUN TO DISCHARGE ONTO THE LOADING PAD.  VANDALISM WAS SUSPECTED BUT NOT CONFIRMED, AS THE GATE WAS STILL LOCKED.  IMMEDIATE ACTION WAS TAKEN TO CLOSE THE OPEN VALVE, AND TO DIKE AND ABSORB THE WASTE.  HOWEVER, PRIOR TO GETTING THE SITUATION TOTALLY UNDER CONTROL, APPROXIMATELY 200 GALLONS HAD BEEN DISCHARGED FROM THE TRAILER, AND APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS HAD MIGRATED TO THE ADJOINING STREET (21ST PLACE).  APPROXIMATELY 10-20 GALLONS ENTERED THE STORM SEWER CATCH BASIN AT THE CORNER OF 21ST PLACE AND ROSEDALE AVE. ALL THE DISCHARGED WASTE WAS ABSORBED USING KILN DUST AND THE SITE AND ADJOINING STREET WERE SWEPT CLEAN.  SINCE IT HAPPENED AT OUR FACILITY, WE WERE ABLE TO VACUUM OUT THE STORM SEWER CATCH BASIN AND MANHOLE PRIOR TO SUCH TIME AS ANY OF THE MATERIAL HAD MIGRATED FURTHER DOWN THE STORM SEWER. ADDITIONAL ABSORBENT WAS THEN USED TO CLEAN UP THE REMAINING WASTE IN THE CATCH BASIN AND MANHOLE.  ALL THE ABSORBED MATERIAL WAS THEN PROPERLY DISPOSED OF AS HAZARDOUS WASTE.

CALIFORNIA DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION PERSONNEL DISCOVERED CHEMICAL RELEASING FROM TRAILER AT SCALE HOUSE.  THE TRAILER WAS ISOLATED TO THE NORTH END OF THE SCALE HOUSE PROPERTY.  THE LOS ANGELES COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM ARRIVED ON-SITE AND MADE ENTRY INTO TRAILER TO FIND SOURCE OF CHEMICAL RELEASE.  IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE (1) FIBERBOARD BOX CONTAINING TWO (2) 1-GALLON JUGS OF ACID WERE BREACHED.  THE LOS ANGELES COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM PROVIDED INITIAL STABILIZATION ACTIONS AND A CLEANUP CONTRACTOR WAS DISPATCHED TO PROVIDE FINAL CLEANUP AND DECONTAMINATION ACTIONS.

DRUM WAS ON DOCK, WE NOTICED THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM WAS WET, FURTHER INSPECTION THE WELD ON THE BOTTOM RIM OF THE DRUM WAS LEAKING.  THERE WAS NO VISIBLE WHOLES IN THE DRUM, CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, TALK TO RICH PETZ AND HE IS CALLING THE MANUFACTURE OF THE PRODUCT.

column168: ON THURSDAY JUNE 10, 2004 AN EXXON MOBIL OIL TANKER AT APPROXIMATELY 7:30 PM WAS TRAVELING  NORTH ON COUNTY ROAD #110. THE TANKER RUPTURED SPILLING 12,000 GALLONS OF GAS.  LOCAL FIRE, POLICE WERE CALLED TO SCENE AS WELL AS DUTCHES COUNTY HAZMAT.  DRIVER WAS GIVEN FIRST AID AT SCENE AND RELAPSED.  DRIVERS WILL BE GIVEN STRICT INSTRUCTIONS TO TRAVEL ALL ROADS USING PROPER SPEED DEPENDING ON ROAD CONDITIONS.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE AT A DROP-YARD IN CHANNAHON, ILLINOIS, FREE PRODUCT WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM THE WERNER ENTERPRISES TRAILER.  WERNER ENTERPRISES CONTACTED THE CHANNAHON FIRE DISTRICT.  WERNER ENTERPRISES DISPATCHED ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION SERVICES, INC. OF MONTGOMERY, ILLINOIS TO PERFORM THE INVESTIGATION AND CLEANUP.  UPON INVESTIGATION, ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION SERVICES, INC. DISCOVERED ONE DAMAGED FIFTY-FIVE GALLON METAL DRUM INSIDE THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY FIVE GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO DAMAGE TO THE CHIMES ON THE SIDES OF THE DRUM, CAUSED BY A CLAMP TRUCK DURING LOADING.  THE DRUM WAS LOADED TIGHTLY AGAINST OTHER DRUMS AND DUE TO VIBRATION IN TRANSIT, A CRACK FORMED ON THE DRUM.  ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION SERVICES, INC. THE PALLET BROKE DURING TRANSIT, CAUSING CONTAINER TO SLIP FROM UNDER STRAP AND FALL ONTO ITS SIDE.  THIS CAUSED A DRIP OF APPROXIMATELY 2 OUNCES OF SULFURIC ACID TO LEAK FROM BUNG OF CONTAINER. THE CONSIGNEE USED ABSORBENT TO CLEANUP AND PROPERLY DISPOSE OF SPILLAGE.

YARD PERSONNEL AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S GENTILLY YARD IN NEW ORLEANS, LA REPORTED AN AMMONIA ODOR COMING FROM GATX51975, LOAD ANHYDROUS AMMONIA. THE CAR WAS MOVED TO THE YARD'S ISOLATION TRACK AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  LOCAL AND STATE EMERGENCY RESPONSE AGENCIES WHERE ALSO NOTIFIED.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER RESPONDED AND FOUND A VAPOR RELEASE WAS COMING FROM AROUND THE TANK NOZZLE FLANGE WHERE THE PRESSURE PLATE IS BOLTED ONTO THE TANK NOZZLE.  USING AN AIR POWERED IMPACT WRENCH, CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER TIGHTENED ALL THE FLANGE BOLTS 1/4 TURN.  THE VAPOR LEAK WAS STOPPED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

GATX70010, LOAD CORROSIVE LIQUID, ACIDIC, ORGANIC, NOS (ALKYLBENZENE SULFONIC ACID) WAS OBSERVED TO SLOSH PRODUCT FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN LIMA, OH.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED ON THE SHIP TRACK AND THE SHIPPER, PROCTER & GAMBLE, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. PROCTER & GAMBLE PERSONNEL RESPONDED FROM THEIR LIMA, OH FACILITY.  THEY REPORTED THAT THE MANWAY COVER WAS COCKED UP IN THE FRONT LEAVING A 1/8 IN GAP BETWEEN THE MANWAY COVER AND THE TANK NOZZLE.  THEY OPENED THE MANWAY COVER AND CHECKED THE GASKET.  IT WAS OK.  THEY CLOSE THE MANWAY COVER, PROPERLY ALIGNED IT, AND SECURED THE MANWAY BOLTS WRENCH TIGHT.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO BE DELIVERED TO PROCTER & GAMBLE.

column72: C I T X (PLM RAILCAR SERV CN)
column168: AT CSC TRANSPORTATION'S YOEMAN YARD, TAMPA, FL, EMPLOYEE ROBERT YOUNG WAS WORKING ON TRACK 8 AND REPORTED HE INHALED SOME AMMONIA VAPORS AND BECOME LIGHT HEADED.  MR. YOUNG WALKED TO THE YARD OFFICE TO REST.  WHEN HE STARTED BACK TO THE YARD, HE PASSED OUT.  EMS TRANSPORTED HIM TO TAMPA GENERAL HOSPITAL WHERE HE RECEIVED A CHEST X-RAY AND A BLOOD GAS TEST.  NO EVIDENCE OF ANY CHEMICAL EXPOSURE WAS FOUND AND MR. YOUNG WAS RELEASED WITHOUT TREATMENT TO RETURN TO WORK.  IN THE MEANTIME, CSXT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INSPECT THE CARS ON TRACK 8.  THE CONTRACTOR DISCOVERED THAT CITX33480, RESIDUE, LAST CONTAINED ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, HAD A SLIGHT VAPOR LEAK AT THE PRODUCT RELIEF DEVICE (PRD).  THEY REPORTED THERE WAS NO DETECTABLE ODOR ON THE GROUND AROUND THE CAR AND ONLY DETECTED THE VAPOR RELEASE BY PLACING THE PROBE OF THEIR AIR MONITOR IN THE UNLOADING PORT OF THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND BOTH THE SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE WERE NOTIFIED.  THE CONTRACTOR SUSPECTED THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A BAD O RING.  THEY ATTEMPTED TO CHANGE OUT THE O RING BUT WAS UNABLE TO REMOVE A RETAINING NUT ON THE ROD OF THE PRD.  CF INDUSTRIES WAS ADVISED OF THE DIFFICULTY.  THEY SENT RESCAR, A RAIL CAR REPAIR CO., TO INSPECT THE PRD.  THE 80 POUNDS OF PRESSURE ON THE CAR WAS BLED OFF THROUGH A WATER BATH.  RESCAR REPLACED O RING AND THE FLANGE GASKET.  THE VAPOR LEAK WAS STOPPED AND THE CAR WILL MOVED TO DESTINATION

REPAIRS WERE MADE BY REACT WHO REPLACE THE DEFICIENT GASKET WITH A TEFLON GASKET.  ALL OTHER VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE EXAMINED AND NO FURTHER EXCEPTIONS NOTED.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1530 HOURS, THE TANK CAR WAS SECURED AND OKAYED FOR DESTINATION.  AS THIS WAS THE SECOND TANK CAR IN AN ACRYLATE SERVICE THAT WAS REPORTED LEAKING IN THE SAME YARD, FROM THE SAME AREA ON THE CAR, ON THE SAME DAY, ALL OTHER SIMILAR CARS WERE INSPECT Y CONRAIL AND REACT PERSONNEL.  NO FURTHER EXCEPTIONS NOTED.

MANWAY COVER'S BUTYL RUBBER GASKET DETERIORATED, PROX 41020, JUNE 4, 2004, SOUTH EAST DIVISION.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0900 HOURS, FRIDAY, JUNE 4, 2004, AT PAVONIA YARD IN CAMDEN, NEW JERSEY, THE PAVONIA ENGINE HOUSE REPORTED A STRONG ODOR.  FURTHER INSPECTION BY CONRAIL'S MANAGER RISK MANAGEMENT AND A REPRESENTATIVE OF REACT FOUND THE ODOR EMANATING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR PROX 41020, LOAD ETHYL ACRYLATE, STABILIZED (ETHYL ACRYLATE).  APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE.  INSPECTION NOTED THE MANWAY COVER'S BUTYL RUBBER GASKET WAS DETERIORATED.  REPAIRS WERE MADE BY REACT WHO REPLACED WITH A TEFLON GASKET.  ALL OTHER VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE EXAMINED AND NO FURTHER EXCEPTIONS NOTED.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1230 HOURS, THE TANK CAR WAS SECURED. THE ENTIRE YARD HAD BEEN SHUT DOWN AT THE INITIAL REPORT.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1010 HOURS, ALL BUT CLASS TRACKS 1-3 WERE REOPENED FOR NORMAL OPERATIONS, TO INSURE SAFETY OF PERSONNEL ADMINISTERING THE REPAIRS.  DOW CHEMICAL CABLE SEAL FOR BREADBOX "020849" REMOVED DURING INSPECTION; AND REPLACED WITH "CR 001736" AT TIME OF SECUREMENT.  DOW CHEMICAL CABLE SEAL FOR MANWAY COVER "020841" REMOVED DURING INSPECTION; AND REPLACE WITH "REACT 000008" AT TIME OF SECUREMENT.

UNIT WAS PRESENTED FOR DELIVERY, DRIVER QUESTIONED OPERATOR ABOUT CAPACITY OF STORAGE TANK AND PLANT DECIDED TO FILL ONE 150 GALLON TOTE OUT OF THE STORAGE TANK BEFORE UNLOADING OUR CARGO TRUCK.  WHEN OUR CARGO TANK WENT EMPTY, THE STORAGE TANK WAS COMPLETELY FULL AND A SURGE OF AIR FROM OUR CARGO TANK BUBBLED UP THROUGH THE STORAGE TANK WHICH BLEW OPEN THE MANWAY TO THE TANK AND APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLON OF ACID SURGED OUT OF THE TANK INTO A CONTAINED TRUCK DOCK AREA THAT HAD WATER IN IT.  SODA ASH AND ADDITIONAL WATER WAS PLACED WITH THE ACID TO NEUTRALIZE IT AND THEN THE MATERIAL WAS PICKED UP AND DISPOSED OF.  PRIMARY CAUSE IF THAT CUSTOMER'S TANK IS TOO SMALL TO ACCEPT COMPLETE FILLING FROM A CARGO TANK, AIR SURGE HAS NO WHERE TO GO.  CARRIER AND SHIPPER WORKING TO RESOLVE CAPACITY ISSUE WITH THIS TANK.

ON JUNE 2, 2004, AT APPROXIMATELY 1530 HOURS, RAILWAY TANK CAR GATX 15458, CONTAINING DIMETHYL SULFIDE, 3, UN 1164, PG II WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING WHILE BEING SWITCHED AT THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) BATON ROUGE, LOUISIANA RAIL YARD.  THE SHIPPER DISPATCHED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM TO THE SITE, WHO REPORTED A DEFECTIVE MANWAY GASKET.  THE RESPONDER REPLACED THE GASKET, THUS CORRECTING THE RELEASE.  THERE WERE NO REPORTED INJURIES OR DAMAGE TO THE ENVIRONMENT, AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED BACK INTO TRANSPORTATION.

column172: Drum - fiber, metal or plastic not specified

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED FIVE GALLON PLASTIC PAIL WAS DISCOVERED ON THE DOCK. APPROXIMATELY ONE QUART OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE DAMAGE TO THE PAIL WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY A NAIL ON THE SKID.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, A DUSTMASK, A SHOVEL AND ABSORBENTS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. OUTSIDE CONTRACTORS (WASTRON, TPH, HARBOR CLEAN AIR AND ENVIRONMENTAL PRODUCTS & SVCS) TESTED AND DECONTAMINATED THE UPS FACILITY, PACKAGE CARS AND POTENTIALLY CONTAMINATED PKGS. TO GO BACK TO FULL OPERATIONS ON 6/22/2004 AT APPROXIMATELY 2300 HRS.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: WHILE UNLOADING FREIGHT AT CONWAY WESTERN EXPRESS-UPW, TRAILER 313-0631 WAS PLACED AT THE DOCK TO BE UNLOADED.  UPON OPENING THE DOOR OF THE TRAILER IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE JUG ON PRO 581399862 WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP WHERE THE CAP IS.  THE FREIGHT WAS TAIL LOADED WITH A TOTAL OF 6 JUGS ON TWO DIFFERENT BOL'S.  THREE JUGS ON EACH BILL.  FIVE OF THE JUGS WERE LOADED ON THE FLOOR WITH ONE JUG STACKED ON TOP OF THE OTHER FIVE.  PALLET USED TO BRACE THE BOTTOM FIVE WAS NOT BIG ENOUGH TO SUPPORT THE TOP JUG THAT THEN FELL OVER AND STARTED TO LEAK.  THIS HAPPENED AT 0200 AM ON 6-18-04.  AT THAT POINT EVERYONE WAS TOLD TO STAY OUT OF THE TRAILER, JEFF TURNER-REGIONAL SAFETY MANAGER WAS CALLED AND NOTIFIED, AT WHICH TIME DIRECTION WAS GIVEN TO CALL CHEMTREC AND THEN CHEMTREC CALLED NALCO WHO QUICKLY CALLED MYSELF BACK AT CONWAY WESTERN EXPRESS.  TRAILER WAS SECURED UNTIL THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CLEANUP CREW COULD BE REACHED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THIS VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON I-55 IN THE VICINITY OF HERNANDO, MS. THE ROAD CONDITIONS WERE HAZARDOUS TO HEAVY RAINFALL.  ALL TRAFFIC WAS MOVING SLOWLY DUE TO HEAVY RAINFALL AND BECAUSE THIS WAS A CONSTRUCTION ZONE AREA.  WITNESSES ESTIMATED OUR VEHICLE'S SPEED TO BE BETWEEN 40 & 50 MPH.  OUR VEHICLE WAS PASSING OTHER VEHICLES AND AS IT PROCEEDED TO MOVE BACK INTO THE RIGHT LANE, THE DRIVER APPLIED THE BRAKES.  THE VEHICLE THEN PROCEEDED TO SKID, AND UPON REACHING THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD, IT BEGAN TO OVERTURN.  THE CARGO TANK, MOUNTED ON THE VEHICLE WAS RUPTURED AND SPILLED IT'S CONTENTS.  THE MISSISSIPPI STATE TROOPER, CALLED TO THE SCENE, SHUT DOWN THE NORTH BOUND LANE OF I-55 FOR A VERY SHORT PERIOD OF TIME, UNTIL THE TANK CONTENTS WERE EMPTIED.

AS SOON AS THE LEAK WAS NOTICED, DELIVERY WAS SHUT DOWN, THE TANK DEPRESSURIZED AND THE AIR FITTING WAS CHANGED OUT.  FOLLOWING REPAIR, DELIVERY WAS COMPLETED WITHOUT ANY FURTHER PROBLEMS.  SPILLED MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND PICK UP BY THE CONSIGNEE.  THE AIR LINE FITTING (CHICAGO FITTING) HAD PIN HOLES THAT WERE NOT DETECTABLE BY NORMAL VISUAL INSPECTION BUT WERE APPARENTLY CAUSED BY EXPOSURE TO ACID AT SOME POINT EVEN THOUGH THE PRODUCT SHOULD NOT BE IN THE AIR LINE, IT IS PROTECTED BY A VALVE BETWEEN THE FITTING AND THE INTERIOR OF THE CARGO TANK.  THE BAD FITTING HAS BEEN REMOVED AND DESTROYED AND REPLACED WITH A NEW UNIT.

CSX TRANSPORTATION RECEIVED A REPORT FROM THE NEW ORLEANS POLICE DEPARTMENT OF CITIZEN COMPLAINTS OF STRONG ODORS COMING FROM A CUT OF RAIL CARS SITTING ON A TRACK NEAR DAHLIA WALK AND EDGE ST.  THE RAIL CARS HAD JUST BEEN RECEIVED IN INTERCHANGE FROM THE CANADIAN NATIONAL RAILROAD.  THE NEW ORLEANS FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZMAT TEAM DETERMINED THAT THE ODOR WAS COMING FROM A UTLX57878, LOAD FLAMMABLE LIQUID NOS (CRUDE SULFATE TURPENTINE). CSX TRANSPORTATION'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR A POSSIBLE LEAK.  THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THAT VAPORS WERE COMING FROM A RUBBER HOSE OVER THE PIPE NIPPLE WHERE THE AIR/VAPOR VALVE SHOULD HAVE BEEN.  THE HOSE WAS CLAMPED OFF WITH 2 HOSE CLAMPS AND WAS WRAPPED IN PLASTIC AND SECURED WITH DUCK TAPE.  THERE WAS NO SIGN OF ANY LIQUID PRODUCT LEAKAGE.  THE NEW ORLEANS FIRE DEPARTMENT GAVE CSXT PERMISSION TO MOVE THE TANK CAR TO OUR GENTILLY YARD AND PLACE IT OVER THE SPILL PAN ON THE HAZMAT ISOLATION TRACK.  THE SHIPPER, INLAND PAPERBOARD, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  INLAND PAPERBOARD ADVISED CSXT THAT THIS TANK CAR WAS DAMAGED ON THE CANADIAN NATIONAL RAILROAD AND WAS MOVING BACK TO THEIR FACILITY FOR REPAIRS WHEN IT WAS INTERCHANGED TO CSXT IN ERROR.  ON 06-13-04, CSXT'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THAT THE ONE AND A QUARTER INCH AIR/VAPOR VALVE HAD BEEN "HAMMERED OVER" AND A WOODEN PLUG WAS DRIVEN INTO THE END OF THE PIPE.  THE WOODEN PLUG WAS SATURATED WITH PRODUCT WHICH ALLOWED VAPORS TO WEEP THROUGH THE WOOD.  THE CONTRACTOR REPLACED THE ONE INCH HOSE WITH A ONE AND A QUARTER INCH HOSE AND PROPERLY CLAMPED THE END OF THE HOSE CLOSED WHICH STOPPED THE VAPOR RELEASE.  INLAND PAPERBOARD IS TO OBTAIN ANOTHER FRA APPROVAL FOR THE MOVEMENT OF THE CAR FROM CSXT BACK TO THE CANADIAN NATIONAL FOR DELIVERY TO THEIR FACILITY AT BOGULUSA, LA.

A SWITCH CREW AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S HOOKERS POINT YARD IN TAMPA, FL, REPORTED AN AMMONIA ODOR AROUND 2 TANK CARS, GATX47957 AND NATX35795, BOTH RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED, ANHYDROUS AMMONIA.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT DISPATCHED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO THE YARD TO INSPECT THE CARS.  THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THAT THE SAMPLE VALVE ON THE GATX47957 WAS OPEN AND THE VALVE WAS PLUGGED WITH A BOLT, NOT A STANDARD VALVE PLUG.  THE CONTRACTOR TOOK 3 TURNS TO CLOSE THE VAPOR VALVE AND THE VAPOR LEAK STOPPED.  THEY REPLACED THE BOLT WITH A STANDARD VALVE PLUG.  NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE WAS FOUND ON THE NATX35795.  THE SHIPPER, CF INDUSTRIES WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC AND WAS ADVISED OF THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE.  CF INDUSTRIES INDICATED THAT THEY WOULD INSPECT THE SAMPLE VALVE AND WOULD REPLACE IT IF NECESSARY.

A BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE DRIP TO CONTAIN THE PRODUCT. THE SHIPPER, OLIN CORP. WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  CSXT'S MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT GENERAL FOREMAN WHO IS ALSO A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SENTINEL RESPONDED.  HE REPORTED THAT THE TOP OPERATING ROD FOR THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS LOOSE. A TRAIN CREW SWITCHING CARS IN CSX TRANSPORTATION'S QUEENSGATE YARD IN CINCINNATI, OH, REPORTED A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM THE AREA AROUND SOME TANK CARS SITTING ON AN ADJACENT TRACK.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INVESTIGATE.  THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THE ODOR WAS COMING FROM AN ACFX79861. LOAD FLAMMABLE LIQUID, NOS, CRUDE SULFATE TURPENTINE.  VAPORS WERE ESCAPING THROUGH THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE (SRV).  THERE WAS AN AUDIBLE HISS AND IT WAS OBVIOUS THAT THE ODOR WAS COMING FROM THE SRV.  THE CONTRACTOR RELIEVED THE PRESSURE IN THE CAR AND THE VAPOR RELEASE STOPPED.  IT WAS SUSPECTED THE SRV WAS NOT PROPERLY SEATED ALLOWING VAPORS TO PASS THROUGH.  THE CONTRACTOR RETURNED LATE THE NEXT DAY (06-25-04) TO CHECK THE PRESSURE ON THE CAR.  THE PRESSURE WAS ABOUT 2 POUNDS PER SQUARE INCH AND VAPORS WERE SEEPING THROUGH THE SRV.  IFF CHEMICAL WHO IS THE LEASEE OF THE CAR WAS ADVISED OF THE CONTRACTOR'S FINDINGS.  IFF CALLED RESCAR, A MOBILE RAIL CAR REPAIR COMPANY, TO RESPOND TO REPAIR THE SRV.  RESCAR RESPONDED ON 06-28-2004 AND REPLACED THE O RINGS IN THE SRV.  THERE WAS NO VAPOR LEAK DETECTED AND THE ODOR HAD DISSIPATED.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

SWITCHER, Y20128, WORKING IN CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN PARKERSBURG, WV, REPORTED TANK CAR, UTLX200915, LOAD COMBUSTIBLE LIQUID, NOS (2-ETHYL HEXYL ALCOHOL), WAS SLOSHING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP WHEN IT WAS MOVED.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER, UNION CARBIDE (DOW CHEM.) WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  DOW CHEMICAL AUTHORIZED CSXT TO SEND AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE.  THE CONTRACTOR RESPONDED ON 06-29-04.  THEY FOUND THAT TWO OF EIGHT MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS WERE NOT FINGER TIGHT.  THEY MADE CERTAIN ALL THE MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS WERE WRENCH TIGHT.  THEY ALSO INSPECTED THE LIQUID VALVE AND THE VAPOR VALVE FINDING THEM TO BE OK.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.  DOW CHEMICAL WAS ADVISED OF THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE.

THE DRIVER WAS IN THE UNLOADING PROCESS WHEN THE REGULATOR THAT CONTROLS THE AMOUNT OF AIR PRESSURE CRACKED CAUSING PRODUCT TO BE RELEASED THROUGH THE BACK OF THE REGULATOR.  THE DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE SYSTEM IMMEDIATELY AND CONTAINED THE SPILL, ALL OF THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED TO AN ASPHALT SURFACE.  SWS ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTACTED TO PERFORM THE CLEAN UP.  THE PRODUCT WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH AND THEN CLEANED UP AND PUT IN DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL.  IN THE INVESTIGATE IT WAS FOUND THAT PRODUCT HAD FOUND ITS WAY INTO THE AIR INLET.  IN ORDER THE PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENT THE AIR PRODUCT LINE HAS BEEN CHANGED AND MOUNTED HIGHER IN THE TANK AWAY FROM THE PRODUCT LEVEL AND A BALL VALVE WAS INSTALLED TO KEPT THE PRODUCT FROM BACK-FLOWING.

A CLOSED BOX BIN CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE SOLID WAS RELEASED FROM A SUDDEN TRAFFIC RELATED STOP.  THE RELEASED MATERIAL IMPACTED AREA, CONSISTING OF A ROADWAY OVER 2.5-3 BLOCKS, AND A SOIL SURFACE, CONSISTING OF AN AREA OF 20 FEET LONG BY 6 FEET WIDE.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED TO PROVIDE INITIAL RESPONSE ACTIONS.  SUBSEQUENTLY, A ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP CONTRACTOR WAS HIRED TO PROVIDE CLEANUP ACTIONS, INCLUDING REMOVAL OF CONTAMINATED SOIL, REMOVAL OF RELEASED CHEMICAL ON ROADWAY, AND A FINAL DECONTAMINATION OF ROAD VIA POWER WASHING OF ROADWAY. CARRIER WILL ENSURE TARP IS SECURE TO BOX BIN TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column168: PRIOR TO SHIPPING THE STEEL DRUM WOULD NOT FORM A SEAL AND WAS PACKAGED INTO AN 85-GALLON SALVAGE DRUM.  WHILE IN TRANSIT THE INNER STEEL DRUM PRESSURIZED AND FAILED.  THE OUTER CONTAINER'S LID THEN BULGED.  WHILE ATTEMPTING TO REMOVE PRESSURE, THE LID POPPED OFF RELEASE A SMALL AMOUNT OF THE WASTE ONTO THE TRUCK'S FLOOR.  THE RELEASED LIQUID WAS PROMPTLY CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP.  THE LIQUID WAS TRANSFERRED TO A NEW DRUM, AND THE DAMAGED DRUMS AND SPILL RESIDUE WAS PACKAGED INTO A 110-GALLON DRUM. IT IS BELIEVED THAT THE MATERIAL OFF GASSED EITHER BECAUSE OF A REACTION OF A CONTAMINANT OR BECAUSE OF DECAY OF ORGANIC MATERIAL IN THE WASTE STREAM. THE ACTIONS TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING IN THE FUTURE WILL BE TO TRANSFER THE LIQUID INTO THE DRUMS SEVERAL DAYS PRIOR TO SHIPPING.  THE MATERIAL CAN THEN BE MONITORED ENSURING NO REACTION OR DECAY WILL OCCUR WHEN IN TRANSIT.

ON 6/28/04 AT APPROXIMATELY 12:00 PM; A TRANSPORT DRIVER FOR GULFMARK ENERGY WAS LOADING HIS TANKER WITH CRUDE OIL AT THE "PWLR #2" LEASE FOR CUMMINS AND WALKER OIL, INC. WHEN LIGHTNING STRUCK THE TANK BATTERY HE WAS LOADING OUT OF.  THE LIGHTNING STRUCK AFTER GULFMARK ENERGY'S DRIVER HAD BEEN LOADING FOR ABOUT 10 MINUTES.  THE STRIKE CAUSED THE 400-BARREL TANK HE WAS LOADING OUT OF TO EXPLODE FROM THE GROUND AND LAND 200 FEET AWAY. THE ENSUING FIRE CONSUMED A LARGE PART OF THE FACILITY AS WELL AS GULFMARK ENERGY'S TRANSPORT.  OUR DRIVER ESCAPED WITH MINOR SCRAPES AND BRUISES HE RECEIVED WHILE FLEEING THE LOCATION.  IT WAS DETERMINED BY THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT THAT THE BEST COURSE OF ACTION WAS TO LET THE FIRE BURN ITSELF OUT.  APPROXIMATELY 60 BARRELS OR 2,500 GALLONS OF CRUDE OIL WAS ONBOARD GULFMARK ENERGY'S TRANSPORT WHEN THE LIGHTNING STRUCK AND FIRE ENGULFED THE AREA.  CUMMINS AND WALKER ARE REPORTING THAT THEY LOST A TOTAL OF 750 BARRELS OR 33,000 GALLONS OF CRUDE OIL IN THIS INCIDENT.

column168: ON JUNE 18, 2004, AT APPROXIMATELY 0900 HOURS, A RAILWAY CAR, ACFX 48961, LOADED WITH HAZARDOUS WASTE, SOLID, N.O.S. (K061), 9, NA 3077, PG III, WAS LEAKING FROM AN OPEN "A" END HOOPER DOOR WHILE BEING INTERCHANGED WITH THE NORFOLK SOUTHERN (NS) IN TUSCALOOSA, ALABAMA.  KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) DISPATCHED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE (ER) TEAM TO THE SITE, AND MADE ALL REQUIRED FEDERAL/STATE/LOCAL AND SHIPPER NOTIFICATIONS.  THE SHIPPER ARRIVED ON SITE AT 1400 HOURS, AND THE KCSR CONTRACTED EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM SECURED THE OPEN HOPPER DOOR.  DURING LOADING, THE SHIPPER HAD NOT SEALED THE CLOSED HOOPER DOORS WITH THE CUSTOMARY NUMBERED SEALS; THEREFORE, THESE SEALS COULD NOT BE TIED TO A LOADING DOCUMENT.  THE SHIPPER DID INDICATE THAT THEIR STANDARD PRACTICE WAS TO CLOSE THE DOOR LATCH AND SECURE THE LATCH WITH BAILING WIRE.  ON JUNE 18 THROUGH JUNE 22, 2004.  KCSR USED SEVERAL VACUUM TRUCKS TO RECOVER RELEASED MATERIALS AND CONTAINERIZE INTO VACUUM BOXES FOR DISPOSAL TO CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT IN EMELLE, ALABAMA.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES, AND THE CAR WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

LOCAL MECHANICAL PERSONNEL PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE DRIP.  THE SHIPPER, CONE SOLVENTS, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR THE LEAK.  THE CONTRACTOR FOUND THAT THE PACKING GLAND NUT AROUND THE TOP OPERATING ROD FOR THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS LOOSE, THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS OPEN AND THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP PLUG WAS LOOSE.  THE OPERATING ROD FOR THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS TURNED 1 1/2 TURNS TO CLOSE THE VALVE, THE PACKING GLAND NUT WAS TURNED 3/4 TURN TO TIGHTEN THE NUT AND THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP PLUG WAS TURNED 1 TURN TO MAKE IT WRENCH TIGHT.  THE LEAK WAS STOPPED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED.  THE SHIPPER WAS ADVISED OF THESE DEFECTS.

THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP WITH A SPILL PAD, PLACED INSIDE OF A PLACED BAG AND RETURNING TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

PREPARING TO OFF LOAD MATERIAL VIA TRACTOR MOUNTED PUMP, THE RECEIVER ADVISED THE DRIVERS THE VALVE WAS OPEN AND TO BEGIN PUMPING THE PRODUCT INTO HIS CONTAINER.  ONCE THE PUMP WAS STARTED, THE PRESSURE BUILT UP IN THE HOSE TO A POINT THAT CAUSED THE HOSE TO FAIL.  THIS WAS A RESULT OF THE RECEIVER NOT OPENING HIS VALVE AND THE PUMP BUILDING UP PRESSURES GREATER THAN THE HOSE COULD WITHSTAND.  DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO ENSURE BY VISUALLY INSPECTING IF POSSIBLE THE RECEIVERS VALVE IS OPEN PRIOR TO THE BEGINNING THE PUMPING PROCESS.  ALSO, ENSURE THE PRESSURE RELIEF BY-PASS ON THE PUMPS ARE OPERATIONAL.

THE DRIVER STAGED THE UNIT ON THE LOADING SCALES TO LOAD MOLTEN SULFUR. WHILE CONNECTING THE SAFETY CHAIN THE DRIVER FAILED TO PULL UP ON THE LOADING ARM TO REMOVE THE SLACK IN THE SAFETY CHAIN.  WHEN THE LOADING PUMP WAS STARTED THE LOADING ARM LIFTED AND THE SAFETY CHAIN CAME DISCONNECTED CAUSE THE LOADING ARM TO COME UP AND OUT OF THE DOME OPENING.  THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED ON IMPERVIOUS SURFACE AND CTL SENT OUT A CREW TO PERFORM THE CLEAN UP.  THE DRIVER WAS SENT OUT WITH A DRIVER TRAINER TO BE EVALUATED AND RE-TRAINED ON LOADING PROCEDURES.

column168: THE DRIVER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF OFF-LOADING AND THE TRACTOR PUMP SHAFT STARTED TO DEVELOP A LEAK.  THE DRIVER SHUT THE OFF-LOADING PROCESS DOWN TO HAVE REPAIRS TO THE TRACTOR PUMP. IN THIS PROCESS OF DISCONNECTING THE DRIVER FAILED TO CLOSE TO DOME LID PRIOR TO MOVING THE UNIT AND AS HE STARTED TO MOVE THE UNIT THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT SOME PRODUCT HAD SPLASHED OUT OF THE DOME AREA.  THE PLANT PERSONNEL PUT SOME ABSORBENT DOWN ON THE SPILLED PRODUCT.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER SECUREMENT PROCEDURES.

REPAIR HAD BEEN MADE TO THIS UNIT REQUIRING THE FRONT WASHOUT CAP TO BE REMOVED.  WHEN THE FRONT WASHOUT CAP WAS RE-INSTALLED THE MECHANIC FAILED TO PROPERLY TIGHTEN DOWN THE CAP.  WHEN THE SURGE FROM THE LIQUID PRODUCT SURGED FORWARD CAUSED ENOUGH FORCE TO FORCE THE WASHOUT CAP OFF THE THREADED NIPPLE.  THE SHOP MECHANIC WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER PROCEDURE IN SECURING OPENINGS.  A TRAINING SESSIONS WAS COMPLETED WITH ALL SHOP MECHANIC ON 6/30/04 TO DISCUSS THE INCIDENT TO GO OVER NEW INSPECTION PROCEDURE TO PREVENT RE-OCCURRENCE.

column168: OUR VEHICLE WAS RETURNING FROM LOGGIN JOB IN NORTHWEST UTAH WHEN THE INSIDE LEFT REAR DUAL TIRE CAUGHT FIRE AND BLEW OUT.  DRIVER AND OTHER COMPANY PERSONNEL ATTEMPTED TO EXTINGUISH FIRE WITH MULTI-PURPOSE FIRE EXTINGUISHERS MEETING THE REQUIREMENTS OF 49 CFR 393.95(A)(2)(I), BUT WERE UNSUCCESSFUL.  THE VEHICLE BURNED; IT WAS A TOTAL LOSS.  AT THE TIME OF THE FIRE OUR VEHICLE WAS TRANSPORTING 7 (RADIOACTIVE) SOURCES.  ALL OF THE SOURCES WERE REMOVED EXCEPT FOR ONE CALIBRATING SOURCE (YELLOW -II LABEL; DOT SPECIFICATION 7, TYPE A PACKAGING).  THE CALIBRATING SOURCE COULD NOT BE REMOVED DUE TO THE SEVERITY OF THE FIRE.  AS SOON AS THE FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED THE AREA AND TRUCK WERE SURVEYED, THE CALIBRATING SOURCE WAS WIPED TESTED AND CHECKED FOR CONTAMINATION.  THERE WAS NO RADIOACTIVE CONTAMINATION.  ALL THE SOURCES WERE TRANSPORTED TO OUR COMPANY STORAGE FACILITY.  THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL IN THIS INCIDENT. HIGHWAY 191 WAS CLOSED FOR MORE THAN ONE HOUR DURING THE FIRE AND CLEANUP, CAUSING THE INCIDENT TO BE REPORTED 49 CFR 171.15(A)(1)(V).

column168: CITISTEEL BAGHOUSE DUST IN RCRA WASTE K061, AND IS LOADED FROM AN ELEVATED SILO INTO TANKER TRUCKS THROUGH AN ENCLOSED LOADING CHUTE.  THE DRIVER FOR THE HAZARDOUS WASTE TRANSPORTER, GENSIMORE TRUCKING, ARRIVED SHORTLY BEFORE 1 A.M. ON JUNE 26 AND IS BELIEVED TO HAVE ATTEMPTED TO LOAD HIMSELF, CONTRARY TO CITISTEEL POLICY.  THE RETRACTABLE LOADING CHUTE APPARENTLY TORE OR WAS IMPROPERLY POSITIONED, AND THE LOAD WAS DROPPED ONTO THE PAVEMENT INSTEAD OF INTO THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVER THEN NOTIFIED CITISTEEL PERSONNEL OF THE SPILL BEFORE LEAVING THE SITE UNLOADED.  CITISTEEL PERSONNEL USED A VACUUM HOSE SYSTEM TO RECOVER THE MATERIAL FROM THE PAVEMENT BACK INTO THE BAGHOUSE SILO, WHICH WAS COMPLETED ON JUNE 27. SINCE THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED ON PAVEMENT AND RECOVERED BACK INTO THE BAGHOUSE SYSTEM, THERE IS NO KNOWN OR EXPECTED ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT.  A KEYLOCK WAS INSTALLED ON LOADING CHUTE TO PREVENT DRIVERS FROM LOADING WITHOUT SUPERVISION.  AN ANNUAL REPLACEMENT OF CHUTE SHALL BE FOLLOWED TO PREVENT MATERIAL FAILURE.  NOTE THIS LOAD WAS NOT SHIPPED SINCE THE SPILL WAS LOADING.  NO FAILURE OF PACKAGING.

column168: VEHICLE #1 WAS NORTHBOUND I-25 IN THE RIGHT LANE.  VEHICLE #2 WAS NORTHBOUND I-25 IN THE LEFT LANE.  VEHICLE #1 WAS PULLING A CAMPER TRAILER THAT BEGAN TO SWERVE RIGHT TO LEFT, VEHICLE #1 THEN JACK KNIFE IN FRONT OF VEHICLE #2.  VEHICLE #1 CORRECTED TO THE RIGHT AND LOST CONTROL, CAUSING THE TRAILER TO COLLIDE WITH THE PASSENGER DOOR OF VEHICLE #2.  VEHICLE #1 AND TRAILER THEN ROLLED 1/4 TIME.  VEHICLE #2 RAN OFF THE LEFT SIDE OF THE ROAD TO AVOID THE TRAILER AND ROLLED 1/4 TIME, IN THE CENTER MEDIAN. VEHICLE #1 AND THE TRAILER CAME REST ON THE RIGHT SHOULDER OF 1-25. VEHICLE #1 WAS FACING IN A SOUTHWEST DIRECTION.  THE TRAILER WAS FACING IN A NORTHEAST DIRECTION.  VEHICLE #2 CAME TO REST ON ITS LEFT SIDE IN THE CENTER MEDIAN, FACING NORTHWEST.  VEHICLE #1 WAS EQUIPPED WITH DUAL AIRBAGS THAT DID NOT DEPLOY.  VEHICLE #2 WAS NOT EQUIPPED WITH AN AIRBAG. DRIVERS NEED TO BE VERY CAREFUL AND OBSERVANT OF CLEARANCES WHEN MOVING FREIGHT AROUND THEIR TRAILERS-ESPECIALLY AROUND AND NEAR HAZARDOUS SHIPMENTS.

RESPOND TO A TRAILER LEAKING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  DISPATCH TIME 300 PM. RESPOND TO UNKNOWN CHEMICAL LEAK.  UPON ARRIVAL OUR SUPERVISOR MADE CONTACT WITH THE DPS OFFICER, TXDOT AND TRIAD'S DRIVER.  THE DRIVER FURNISHED HWY 59 WITH THE SHIPPING MANIFEST.  AFTER REVIEWING THE MANIFEST WE DISCOVERED THERE WAS A POSSIBILITY OF THREE DIFFERENT CHEMICALS THAT COULD BE LEAKING. TOXIC ORGANIC SOLIDS UN#2811, ORGANOPHOSPHORUS PESTICIDES TOXIC LIQUID UN#3018, AND TOLUENE METHANOL FLAMMABLE LIQUID UN#1993.  A SITE SAFETY MEETING WAS HELD AND A PLAN OF ACTION WAS DISCUSSED.  THEN ENTRY WAS MADE INTO THE TRAILER TO FIND CAUSE OF LEAK.  ONE TEAM OF TECHS WAS TO MAKE ENTRY INTO TRAILER WITH A BACK UP TEAM ON READY STATUS ON SITE WITH PROPER DECON IN PLACE.  SCBA AND SARNEX SUITES WERE REQUIRED DUE TO CONFINED SPACE OF CHEMICALS.  THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED TO BE A DRUM OF TOLUENE LOCATED IN THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER.  THE DRUM HAD A PIN HOLE LEAK ABOUT ONE FOOT FROM THE TOP.  A TEMPORARY PATCH WAS PLACED ON THE DRUM.  HWY 59 THEN PROCEEDED WITH REMOVAL OF THE LIQUIDS FROM THE DRUM WITH OUR VACUUM TRAILER.  HWY 59 ALSO PLACED ABSORBENTS IN THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER ON THE CONTAMINATED AREA TO CONTAIN THE LIQUIDS.  AFTER CONTAINMENT OF THE LIQUIDS WAS COMPLETED HWY 59 REMOVED THE BULK OF THE CONTAMINATED SOIL ON THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD AND PLACED THEM IN A 55 GALLON DRUM.  THE TRUCK AND TRAILER WAS ESCORTED TO OUR MARSHALL TX. YARD.  AT THE YARD HWY 59 REMOVED THE EMPTY DRUM OF TOLUENE AND PLACED IT IN A POLY DRUM OVER PACK.  THE OVER PACK WAS PLACED BACK ON TRIAD'S TRAILER.  HWY 59 THEN COMPLETED THE EXTERNAL CLEAN UP OF THE CONTAMINANTS FROM THE OUTSIDE RIGHT FRONT CORNER OF THE TRAILER.  A CALL WAS PLACED TO CHRIS WITH TRIAD TO UPDATE TRIAD. THEN THE TRUCK AND TRAILER WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE HIS TRIP.  ON 07-02-2004 HWY 59 RETURNED TO THE JOB SITE ON I-20 AND REMOVED RESIDUAL CONTAMINANTS IN THE SOIL'S, THAT WERE MISSED THE NIGHT OF THE SPILL.  THE CONTAMINANTS WERE PLACED IN A 55 GALLON DRUM FOR DISPOSALS ON A FUTURE DATE.

column168: THE DRIVER OF OUR LIQUID NITROGEN TRANSPORT HAD JUST FINISHED FUELING THE TRUCK AND WAS EN ROUTE TO OUR LOCAL FACILITY IN CHINOOK MT TO WAIT FOR ANOTHER DRIVER TO ACCOMPANY HIM TO MALTA MT.  WHILE NEGOTIATING A NINETY DEGREE LEFT TURN THE TRANSPORT UPSET ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE AND SLID OFF OF THE ROADWAY INTO THE DITCH.  ALTHOUGH THE INNER VESSEL DID NOT RUPTURE THE OUTER JACKET WAS DAMAGED ENOUGH TO LOSE VACUUM.  THIS TYPE OF TRANSPORT RELIES ON A VACUUM BETWEEN THE OUTER SHELL AND INNER VESSEL FOR INSULATION. ONCE THE VACUUM WAS LOST THE PRODUCT BEGAN TO WARM MORE QUICKLY RAISING THE PRESSURE FASTER THAN THE RELIEF MECHANISMS COULD HANDLE DUE TO THE FACT THAT THE UNIT WAS ON ITS SIDE AND ALL OF THE VAPOR LINES WERE BELOW THE LIQUID LEVEL.  TO AVOID LETTING THE PRESSURE EXCEED DESIGN CAPABILITIES A DECISION WAS MADE BY SANJEL PERSONNEL TO VENT THE LIQUID THROUGH WHATEVER VALVEING WAS AVAILABLE.  THIS WAS DONE BY RESPONDING CHINOOK FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL.  THE LIQUID NITROGEN WAS ALLOWED TO POOL IN THE DITCH WHERE IT VAPORIZED AND DISPERSED OVERNIGHT.  THIS ACCIDENT WAS THE RESULT OF DRIVER ERROR.  SPECIFICALLY THE DRIVERS SPEED AND IMPROPER BRAKING TECHNIQUE IN CONSIDERATION OFF THE LOAD HE WAS CARRYING.  THE ROAD SURFACE WAS LEVEL AND DRY.  THE POSTED SPEED LIMIT WAS THIRTY MILES PER HOUR, HOWEVER A CAUTIONARY SIGN SUGGESTED TWENTY MILES PER HOUR ON THIS PARTICULAR CURVE.  MONTANA HIGHWAY PATROL CALCULATED HIS SPEED AT TWENTY FIVE TO THIRTY MILES PER HOUR, WITHIN THE LEGAL LIMIT, BUT OVER THE SUGGESTED SAFE SPEED.  THE DRIVER WAS NOT CITED FOR SPEEDING BUT AS A RESULT OF HIS FAILURE TO SAFELY NEGOTIATE HIS SELECTED ROUTE, HIS EMPLOYEE WITH SANJEL WAS TERMINATED.  PART VII - RECOMMENDATIONS/ACTIONS TAKEN TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.  1.  WE ESTABLISHED A POLICY WHERE ALL LIQUID BULK TRUCKS ARE OPERATED TEN MILES PER HOUR UNDER THE POSTED SPEED LIMIT.  2. WE ESTABLISHED A POLICY WHERE ALL CAUTIONARY SIGNS ARE STRICTLY ADHERED TO. 3.  ALL DRIVERS RECEIVE ADDITIONAL TRAINING FOR LIQUID BULK TRANSPORTS PRIOR TO DRIVING SUCH LOADS.  THE TRAINING EMPHASIZES THE UNIQUE CHARACTERISTICS OF LARGE LIQUID LOADS AND THE EFFORTS THAT MUST BE MADE TO SAFELY TRANSPORT THEM.  4.  BECAUSE THE INCIDENT WAS THE DIRECT RESULT OF DRIVER ERROR NO RECOMMENDATIONS CAN BE MADE AS FAR AS INDUSTRY IMPROVEMENT. STANDARD OPERATION PROCEDURES ALREADY IN PLACE, HAD THEY BEEN PROPERLY ADHERED TO, WOULD HAVE PREVENTED THIS ACCIDENT.  IT IS A VIVID REMINDER OF A CONSTANT CHALLENGE WE FACE TO ENSURE THAT OUR EMPLOYEES DOD NOT GET COMPLACENT, LAZY, OR SLOPPY AND DO PERFORM THEIR DUTIES AT THE HIGHEST LEVEL OF COMPETENCY.

column168: THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT THE DRUM HAD LEAKED ONTO FLOOR OF THE VAN.  HE ATTEMPTED, BY HIMSELF, TO PLACE THE DAMAGED DRUM INTO AN "OVERSIZED DRUM" BUT DROPPED IT.  IT ROLLED OFF THE VAN AN ONTO THE ASPHALT BELOW CAUSING A 12 X 10 FOOT SPILL.  ONYX WAS CALLED FOR THE CLEAN-UP.

OUR DRIVER WAS UNLOADING 7500 GALLONS OF LOW SULFUR DIESEL.  WHILE UNLOADING HE OVERFILLED THE ABOVEGROUND TANK, SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 100-120 GALLONS OF FUEL.  THIS INCIDENT WAS OUR DRIVERS ERROR.  PRIOR TO UNLOADING THE DRIVER IS TO MAKE SURE THAT THE TANK WILL HAVE ROOM FOR THE PRODUCT HE IS UNLOADING.  THIS DRIVER DID NOT ASSURE HIMSELF THAT THE TANK WOULD HOLD THE LOAD OF FUEL.  THIS POLICY IS STATED IN OUR DRIVER HANDBOOK AND THIS PROCEDURE IS TAUGHT TO EACH DRIVER WHILE IN TRAINING THAT ALL DRIVERS MUST MAKE SURE THAT ANY TANK WHETHER UNDERGROUND OR ABOVE GROUND WILL HOLD THE PRODUCT BEING DELIVERED.  THEY MUST MEASURE THE TANK AND ASSURE THEMSELVES THAT THE PRODUCT WILL FIT.  IF THEY ARE UNABLE TO VERIFY THAT THE PRODUCT WON'T FIT, THEY ARE NOT TO ULOAD UNTIL THEY ARE ABLE TO MAKE SURE THE TANK WILL HOLD THE PRODUCT.  BECAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT, WE HAVE SENT A MEMO TO ALL DRIVERS TO REMIND THEM THAT THEY MUST MAKE SURE THAT THE TANKS ARE UNLOADING INTO CAN HOLD THE PRODUCT.  THIS ITEM OF UNLOADING AND LOADING IS COVER UNDER OUR DRIVERS MANUAL THAT EACH DRIVER RECEIVES AT THE TIME OF HIRING AND ALSO THIS PROCEDURE IS TAUGHT TO EACH NEW DRIVER BY THE TRAINING DRIVER.  CLEAR HARBORS WAS CALLED TO CLEAN UP SPILL.  BOOMS & ABSORBENT PADS WERE PUT DOWN.  SITE WAS CLEANED UP.

column168: Ruptured hose. The spill situation was extended because the emergency shutdown designed sequence closed the railcar vent valve preventing release of the pressure on the railcar. Third party failure analysis of the hose revealed a defect in the hose lining on unknown origin. Hose had been is use about one month at time of failure.    DETAILS of INCIDENT  At about 16:40 hr, the rail car unloading operator began unloading railcar PROX 16407 that contained 198,150 pounds of sulfuric acid. At about 17:00 hr, the unloading operator noted that the rail car appeared to be getting wet. He investigated and discovered sulfuric acid spraying on to the top of the rail car from a ruptured acid unloading hose. He immediately activated the emergency stop from a remote location, reported the release to plant personnel and began isolating the spill area by barricading the area with “Danger” tape. MDE was notified of the release at about 17:42. Since it appeared to be taking a long time for the pressure to dissipate, the plant air was manually closed upstream away from the spill area just in case the emergency stop had not functioned properly. Clean Harbors, a Haz Mat clean up company, was contacted to mobilize in preparation to clean up the area once the spill was stopped.    The emergency stop closes the air supply valve that supplies air pressure to unload the rail car. It also closes the sulfuric acid discharge and the air supply vent valve. This essentially shuts down the railcar. However, the railcar was under pressure and relieving through the unloading hose that had ruptured. The spray from the hose made it unsafe to approach the top of the railcar to vent the rail ca:r. Thus, the leak was allowed to continue to dissipate the pressure until it was safe to vent the railcar. The acid was spraying on top of the railcar, into the containment area, over the containment area wall onto a gavel area where some piping was temporarily stored and contractor equipment was parked. Some of the acid got onto a plant roadway and flowed into a plant drain that leads to the on site water reclamation plant where the acid was neutralized.    MDE arrived at about 18:13 hr. The spray was continuing as the rail car de-pressurizing. At about 19:30 hrs the MDE recommended that we advise the local fire department and LEPC of our s:ituation. Grace agreed and the MDE responder contacted the Baltimore City Fire Department. They arr:ved at about 19:45. We discussed the situation with them and determined that the rail car could be vented by cutting the air supply hose. This would allow the trapped air pressure in the rail car to back vent through the one-inch hose. Two fire fighters donned level “A” suits and proceed to the top of the railcar and cut the air hose at 20:30 hr. The railcar vented air through the cut hose and the spray ceased at 20:45. The Fire Department offered to wash down the spill area with their high volume fog nozzle. The company agreed and the area was washed for ab
column169: Preventive Actions  1. Changed hose specification  2. Redesigned emergency stop sequence so that the railcar vent opens.

column168: DKE had scheduled a shipment containing a consolidation of caustic waste from Tank T-312 and a 12% oil/oily emulsion solution from bin number 576 to be shipped off-site to an alternate TSDF for treatment and disposal.  Prior to shipment, on June 4, 2004, DKE had sent a pre-shipment sample and waste  profile to DeMenno/Kerdoon for waste acceptance approval into their facility. On June 5,  2004 DeMenno/Kerdoon approved the waste profile for acceptance. A compatibility test  of equal amounts sampled from tank T-312 and the liquid portion from bin number 567  showed no evidence of reactivity when combined. (See attachment 1)  On 6/7/03 at approximately 2:15 p.m. the truck arrived at DKE. DKE personnel and the driver began to transfer (pump) 2,500 gallons of the caustic waste from tank T-31into his vacuum truck. The transfer was completed within 20 minutes, occurring during the time of 2:30 p.m. and 2:50 p.m.  At approximately 3:00 p.m. DKE personnel and the driver began to pump 2,000 gallons  of the liquid portion (oil/ oily emulsion) from bin number 576. The transfer was completed within 30 minutes.  At about 4:15 p.m. the Operations Manager observed steam and liquid releasing from the truck vacuum trailer’s center manway. Operations Manager began to order for an absorbent berm to be created to contain the release.  At 4:30 p.m. the Operations Manager requested that the Compliance Manager call 911 and report the release and request assistance from the Vernon Fire Department. DKE personnel were ordered to evacuate the facility.  At approximately 4:35 p.m. the Vernon Fire Department arrived and was informed that there appeared to be a reaction occurring within the truck vacuum trailer. Copies of the hazardous waste manifest, MSDS, waste profile, and laboratory analytical were available and presented to the Fire Department. U.S. Aluminum, neighboring business to the East, was evacuated and access to 26th street was prohibilled for approximately 5 hours.  DKE and The Vernon Fire Department agreed that cooling the exterior surface of the truck vacuum trailer with water until the reaction had settled or completed its process was the best mitigation procedure. (See attachment 2)  City water was used to cool the truck in timed intervals and temperature readings were taken of the exterior surface of the trailer and recorded. The temperature reading at about 6:00 p.m. was approximately 250°F.  At 5:30 p.m. DKE called out Asbury Environmental Services Emergency Response Unit to provide assistance with the incident. Arrival time was approximately 7:00 p.m.  At 8:00 p.m. the truck appeared stable and was cool enough so that samples could be taken from the truck vacuum container. At 8:30 p.m. the ER Entrance Team took samples. The Vernon Fire Department performed Hazcat testing on one sample and two other samples were sent to DeMenno/Kerdoon, a state certified lab, for analysis. The Hazcat results, although not conclusive, did indicate alkali metals within the sl
column169: The facility must constantly be aware that the Generators do not always describe their waste properly.      Since the facility has not previously received the silicon containing waste, all employees will be trained as to the hazards and compatibility issues of elemental silicon and the proper handling and management of elemental silicon containing wastes.      Any bulk waste designated for consolidation containing multiple layers must have each layer tested separately for compatibility even if the other layers are not intended to be included in the consolidation, since it is possible for portions of the other layers to be included and mixed during the consolidation process.

column168: DURING THE SORT THE PACKAGE FELL TO THE FLOOR AND THE INNER CONTENTS BROKE. THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED AND RECOVERED USING SCU PROCEDURES.  THE PACKAGE WAS THEN PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE SPILLAGE LEADING TO THE DISCOVERY OF THE DISCREPANCY WAS NOTICED.  THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL FOUR METAL CANS AT APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON CAPACITY EACH.  THE LID SEAL ON TWO OF THE FOUR CANS APPARENTLY FAILED ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL.  AN MSDS (MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET) WAS REQUESTED AND OBTAINED FROM THE SHIPPER. THE INFORMATION ON THE DOCUMENT SHOWED THE MATERIAL TO BE DEFINED AS AN ADHESIVE WITH A FLASHPOINT OF 54'F.  THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS OFFERED WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE FAA FOR INVESTIGATION. TELEPHONE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO SPECIAL AGENT KEN HOLMAN/FAA/MEM AT 09:00 (CST) ON 06/08/2004.

ON JUNE 1, 2004, CHRIS HARLEY OF SOLAR WAS DELIVERING A LOAD OF NO. 2 DIESEL TO THE BULK TANKS ADJACENT TO THE VEHICLE MAINTENANCE SHOP ON THE PLANT SIDE.  WHILE MR. HARLEY WAS IN HIS CAB IDLING UP HIS ENGINE, HIS MAIN PUMP BEGAN TO VIBRATE VIOLENTLY CAUSING THE QUICK RELEASES ON HIS PUMP HOSE TO COME LOOSE.  THIS RESULTED IN A SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL ONTO A PAVED AREA.  OVID ARGUELLO, TRACY MCCONNELL AND THE DRIVER REACTED QUICKLY TO STOP THE FLOW OF MATERIAL AND CONTAIN THE SPILL. SPILL CLEANUP REQUIRED 8 LABORERS AND 2 HOURS TO CLEAN UP AND STORE.

column168: UPRR S RESPONSE MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATIONS CENTER NOTIFIED LANE SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY OF A CONTAINER LEAKING AT THE 18TH STREET YARD.  MR. SEKAVEC WAS IN CHICAGO FOR INTERMODAL INSPECTIONS AND CONTACTED HAZ-MAT RESPONSE TO HANDLE THE INCIDENT.  CONTAINER CHIU 25079 WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING LIQUID ONTO THE FLAT CAR.  MR. SEKAVEC MADE CONTACT WITH THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE NUMBER FOR THE SHIPPER, CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL OF KIMBALL, NE, FOR GUIDANCE.  BRAD BECKER WITH HAZ-MAT RESPONSE ASSESSED THE RAIL CAR AND CONTAINER AND ADVISED MR. SEKAVEC THAT THE RELEASED LIQUID WAS CONFINED PREDOMINANTLY TO THE FLAT CAR WITH A MINOR AMOUNT SPILLED ONTO THE BALLAST.  HAZMAT RESPONSE PERSONNEL STOPPED THE LEAK BY TIGHTENED LOOSE BOLTS ON THE END DOOR OF THE ROLL-OFF CONTAINER. THEY ABSORBED THE LIQUID THAT WAS SPILLED ON THE CAR AS WELL AS PICKED UP THE EFFECTED BALLAST AND PLACED ALL OF THE CONTAMINATED MATERIAL INTO A FIVE GALLON BUCKET FOR DISPOSAL BY CLEAN HARBORS.  THE CAR/CONTAINER WAS THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE IN TRANSPORTATION.  NO OTHER IMPACT IS EXPECTED FROM THIS INCIDENT.

column168: LARRY, SIGNAL, REPORTED RAILCAR TIMX 201030 WAS VENTING A VAPOR INTO THE AIR IN SEDALIA, MO.  JOHN MILLER, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED.  MR. MILLER REQUESTED CHEMTREC NOTIFICATION.  AT 8:45 AM, GLEN SPRINGFIELD, SHIPPER, ADVISED THAT THE RAILCAR HAD JUST BEEN IN THE SHOP FOR MAINTENANCE AND HAD THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE REPLACED.  HE FURTHER ADVISED THAT IF THE DEVICE DID NOT RESEAT ITSELF THE REMAINDER OF THE LOAD WOULD DISPERSE.  AT 10:00 AM, MILLER WAS NOTIFIED THAT THE CAR WAS STILL DISPERSING PRODUCT OUT THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE AND IT APPEARED THAT IT WAS NOT GOING TO RESEAT ITSELF.  AT 12:30PM, MILLER WAS ADVISED BY GLEN SPRINGFIELD THAT THE TANK CAR HAD BEEN PARTIALLY OFF-LOADED ON TWO OCCASIONS.  THE REMAINDER OF THE LOAD WAS DISPERSED THROUGH THE DEFECTIVE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE.

AT 0955HRS ON 6-12-04, CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THAT MGR YARD OPERATIONS JOHN VALLEY HAD REPORTED TANK CAR UTLX 642109 TO BE LEAKING IN THE LIVONIA YARD, LIVONIA, LA.  APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT HAD LEAKED DOWN THE SIDES OF THE CAR.  PRODUCT APPEARED TO BE COMING FROM UNDER THE COMBINATION HOUSING.  THE CAR HAD BEEN ISOLATED IN THE HAZMAT SET-OUT TRACK.  CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1100HRS, DAVE RIGGS, CORPORATE DIRECTOR EMERGENCY RESPONSE & SECURITY FOR GEORGIA GULF NOTIFIED LERCH THAT FRANK VENDT, SHIPPING SUPERINTENDENT FROM THE PLAQUEMINE PLANT WAS RESPONDING TO THE SCENE.  ON HIS ARRIVAL AND INSPECTION OF THE CAR, MR VENDT REQUESTED ASSISTANCE FROM UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS DUE TO A FAILED LIQUID VALVE FLANGE GASKET.  THE GASKET WAS REPLACED AND THE CAR SECURED FROM ANY FURTHER LEAKAGE.  THE SIDES OF THE CAR AND HAZMAT TRACK WERE CLEANED OF ANY PRODUCT.  CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE ONTO DESTINATION.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS, WATERWAYS, OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.

RICHARD WULFF, MECHANICAL CAR MANAGER, REPORTED THAT THERE WERE SEVERAL RESIDUE TANKCARS AT THE ALTON-SOUTHERN YARD IN EAST ST LOUIS, IL AND THAT ONE OF THEM WAS APPARENTLY VENTING.  JOHN MILLER, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  MILLER DETERMINED THAT THE MANWAY BOLTS ON SRIX 30124 WERE NOT SECURED, AND THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE WAS BROKEN.  MR. MILLER STATED EMERGENCY REPAIRS WERE MADE ON THE TANKCAR, AND PERMANENT ONES WOULD BE MADE WHEN THE PARTS WERE AVAILABLE.  THE MANWAY BOLTS ON THE HOUSING WERE ALL PROPERLY SECURED.  ON 6/26/04, THE SHIPPER REPLACED THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE.

ON 06/14/2004 AT APPROX: 16:00HRS CTS MGR. M. KELLY WAS NOTIFIED THAT THE ABOVE TANKCAR HAD A STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA COMING FROM IT.  WHEN KELLY ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AND INSPECTED THE CAR HE FOUND THAT THE CAR HAD A 150 PSI ON IT AND THAT THE VAPOR LEAK WAS COMING FROM BETWEEN THE PRESSURE PLATE AND THE MANWAY NOZZLE.  KELLY ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE PRESSURE PLATE BOLTS TO STOP THE LEAK BUT WAS UNABLE TO DO SO.  KELLY THEN PROCEEDED TO DEPRESSURE THE TANKCAR OFF INTO VACUUM TRUCKS LOADED WITH WATER UNTIL IT SHOWED TO HAVE 0 PSI AND THERE WERE NO LONGER ANY ODORS COMING FROM THE CAR.  THE SHIPPER TERRA NITROGEN WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED THAT WHEN THEY RECEIVED MOVEMENT APPROVAL FROM THE FRA THE CAR WOULD CONTINUE ONTO IT'S DESTINATION.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: JIM, TRAINMASTER, REPORTED THE LEAKING OF A CONTAINER IN THE ALTON SOUTHERN YARD IN EAST ST. LOUIS, IL.  JOHN MILLER, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  SPENCER AT CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED. AT 03:00 AM, MILLER DETERMINED THAT A DEFECTIVE MANWAY GASKET WAS THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE.  MILLER ADVISED THAT HE HAD BEEN IN CONTACT WITH MERISOL, THE SHIPPER, AND A REPLACEMENT GASKET WOULD BE LOCATED AND INSTALLED THE FOLLOWING MORNING.  THE RAILCAR WAS ISOLATED IN THE YARD AND SECURED.  ON 06/21/04 AT 10:30 AM, MILLER ADVISED THAT A MANUFACTURED MANWAY GASKET HAD BEEN INSTALLED ON THE TANKCAR, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  THE TANKCAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: AT 1315HRS ON 6-20-04, CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THAT ROBERT TABB, SENIOR MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS HAD REPORTED TANK CAR PROX 32114 VENTING IN THE BASIN YARD, TRACK #2.  THE RMCC MADE SHIPPER NOTIFICATION VIA CHEMTREC.  ON ARRIVAL AND INSPECTION OF CAR, MGR LERCH NOTED THE CAR VENTING FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE.  CAR GAUGED AT 2 INCHES OF OUTAGE, AND TANK PRESSURE MEASURED 210 PSI.  AFTER DETERMINING NATURE OF RELEASE, MGR LERCH REQUESTED ASSISTANCE OF HOUSTON HAZMAT TEAM, AND UPON THEIR ARRIVAL REPLACED THE FAILED O-RING IN THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE.  CONTACT WAS MADE WITH EXXON MOBIL EMERGENCY RESPONSE COORDINATOR ALLEN HUNSBERGER FROM BATON ROUGE, LA.  MR HUNSBERGER WAS ADVISED OF THE CONDITION OF THE CAR., AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TAKEN.  HE INDICATED THAT A RESPONSE TEAM WAS BEING DISPATCHED, AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE BEING MADE TO CONDUCT A LOAD REDUCTION THE FOLLOWING MORNING.  ON 6-21-04, EXXON MOBIL PERSONNEL TRANSFERRED APPROXIMATELY 3640 GALLONS OF PRODUCT INTO TRUCK PROVIDING 21.5 INCHES OF OUTAGE TO TANK CAR PROX 32114.  PRODUCT WAS THEN TRUCKED TO AN EXXON MOBIL FACILITY IN BAYTOWN, TX.  CAR PROX 32114 WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE ONTO DESTINATION, AND AFTER OFF LOADING, WILL BE SHOPPED FOR COMPLETE INSPECTION. column168: JOHN ALLEN, YARDMASTER, REPORTED SIX TANKCARS WITH HAZMAT LOADS, HAD A STRONG ODOR FROM THEM.  THE TANKCARS WERE BEING SET OUT FROM TRAIN QHONL 23.  BOTH ED FEDRICK, SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT, AND KENNETH SIMPSON, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WERE NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  MR. SIMPSON INSPECTED ALL SIX OF THE TANK CARS AND FOUND THAT TANK CAR GATX 10030 HAD A DETERIORATED MANWAY GASKET.  MR SIMPSON REMOVED THE OLD GASKET AND REPLACE IT WITH A NEW MANWAY GASKET.  HE THEN SECURED THE MANWAY BOLTS.  THE LEAK STOPPED AND MR SIMPSON RELEASED THE TANK CAR TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

KIM KEELING, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, REPORTED THREE POSSIBLE LEAKING TANKCARS AT THE BAILEY YARD IN NORTH PLATTE, NE.  AT 4:49 PM, KEELING ADVISED THAT HIS INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT TANKCAR GATX 91770 WAS LEAKING.  CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER, TRIAD NITROGEN WERE NOTIFIED.  A LEAK FROM THE GAUGING ROD PACKING GLAND WAS REPAIRED BY TIGHTENING THE PACKING GLAND NUT, BUT THE TANK CAR WAS STILL LEAKING.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, A LEAK WAS FOUND ON THE "A" END OF THE PRESSURE PLATE.  A 3/4 INCH DRIVE RACHET AND WRENCH WERE USED TO TIGHTEN THE TEN NUTS ON THE "A" SIDE OF THE PRESSURE PLATE.  THIS SLOWED THE LEAK, BUT DID NOT STOP IT. SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE, DAVE, ASKED KEELING TO TRY AN IMPACT WRENCH ON THE NUTS.  BY USING THE IMPACT WRENCH, KEELING WAS ABLE TO APPLY ENOUGH TORQUE TO SECURE THE LEAK.  THE CAR WAS RESEALED.  THE FOLLOWING MORNING, THE TANK CAR WAS GAUGED AT 13.5 INCHES AND THE PRESSURE WAS 150 PSI.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED ON 06/24/04 AT 10:00 HRS.

column168: BACKGROUND: PETE STIMELING, AN HB DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE TO NEPTUNE WWTP.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE FACILITY MR. STIMELING PREPARED TO MAKE THE DELIVERY.  ONCE ALL CONNECTIONS WERE MADE MR. STIMELING ATTEMPTED TO OPEN THE DISCHARGE VALVE AND WAS UNSUCCESSFUL.  HE THEN ACQUIRED A PRY BAR FROM THE CUSTOMER TO ASSIST IN OPENING THE VALVE. AS MR. STIMELING APPLIED PRESSURE IN A FURTHER ATTEMPT TO OPEN THE VALVE THE VALVE STEM SNAPPED.  AT THIS POINT MR. STIMELING ARRIVED AT THE CONCLUSION THE VALVE WAS ALREADY OPEN AND HAD BEEN THAT WAY SINCE LEAVING THE FACILITY.  MR. STIMELING THEN CONTACTED JIM FLEISHER (HB-DISPATCHER) AND INFORMED HIM OF THE SITUATION.  NEXT, HE CONTACTED ROGER CRANE (HB-MAINTENANCE SUPERVISOR) TO DISCUSS THE SITUATION.  MR. CRANE INFORMED MR. STIMELING THE THAT COMPANY THAT INSPECTS HB'S TANKERS (MOBILE TANK INSPECTION, INC. [MTI]) WAS LOCATED IN NEPTUNE AND HE WOULD HAVE A TECHNICIAN SENT OUT TO REPAIR/REPLACE THE VALVE.  THE TECHNICIAN FROM MTI ARRIVED AND REPLACES THE VALVE.  ONCE THE NEW VALVE WAS INSTALLED, MR. STIMELING RECONNECTED AND STARTED TO UNLOAD THE SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE.  THE COMPOUND USED TO SECURE THE NEW VALVE WAS NOT DRY ENOUGH AND A SMALL LEAK/DRIP WAS DETECTED.  AT THIS POINT THE TECHNICIAN CLIMB UP ON TOP OF THE TANKER TO INSPECT THE LEAK.  AS SOON AS THE TECHNICIAN CLIMBED ON TO THE TOP OF THE TANKER THE NEW VALVE FAILED COMPLETELY RELEASING SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE.  THE AIR WAS IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF THE DRIVER AND THE TECHNICIAN MADE THERE WAY TO THE SAFETY SHOWER, AND THE NEPTUNE EMPLOYEES WORKED TO CONTAIN THE SPILL.  AN ESTIMATED 30 TO 100 GALLONS WAS LOST ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT.  AFTER SHOWERING MR. STIMELING CONTACTED THE BRANCH TO REPORT THE INCIDENT.  AFTER EXITING THE SAFETY SHOWER NEITHER REQUIRED NOR REQUESTED MEDICAL ATTENTION.  THE DRIVER HAD BEEN WEARING ALL REQUIRED PPE, THE TECHNICIAN HAD NOT.  THE TECHNICIAN CHANGED CLOTHES THEN PROCEEDED TO INSTALL A FLANGED VALVE TO COMPLETE THE OFF LOAD.  PAUL ODONNEL (UNIVAR HB-BOM) CONTACTED THE FACILITY REPRESENTATIVE, CHRIS KELLY, TO OBTAIN ALL PERTINENT INFORMATION AND TO DETERMINE IF ADDITION ASSISTANCE WAS NEEDED FOR CLEANUP.  AT THIS TIME MR. KELLY STATED THAT THE FACILITY HAD THE MEANS TO HANDLE THE CLEAN UP AND DID NOT REQUIRE ANY ASSISTANCE FORM UNIVAR.  DURING THE INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THIS WAS THE FIRST TRIP THIS TANKER WAS USED SINCE RETURNING FROM BEING REPAIRED AT AN OFF SITE LOCATION.  THE HB SR. FLEET MECHANIC WAS INTERVIEWED AND HE COULD NOT CONFIRM EITHER WAY IF THE VALVE WAS OPEN OR CLOSED WHEN THE TANKER RETURNED FROM BEING REPAIRED.  NEXT, THE INDIVIDUAL THAT LOADED THE TANKER WAS INTERVIEWED AND WAS ADAMANT THAT THE VALVE WAS CLOSED AT THE TIME THE TANKER WAS LOADED.  MR. STIMELING CONFIRMED THAT DURING HIS PRE-TRIP HE INSPECTED THE VALVE AND "THOUGHT" IT WAS CLOSED.

BACKGROUND: A UNIVAR-HB DRIVER, DEE BARNES, WAS MAKING A LTL DELIVERY AT SPRING GLEN FRESH FOODS OF FOUR DRUMS FERRIC CHLORIDE.  WHILE MAKING THE DELIVERY ONE OF THE FOUR DRUMS FELL FROM THE TRUCKS LIFTGATE ONTO THE GROUND.  UPON IMPACT THE TOP OF THE DRUM AND THE BUNG FAILED CAUSE THE LOSS OF APPROXIMATELY TWENTY-FIVE GALLONS OF PRODUCT ONTO THE GRAVEL ROADWAY. THE SPILLED MATERIAL IMMEDIATELY SOAKED INTO THE ROADWAY AND THE BREECHED DRUM WAS UP-RIGHTED CONTAINING THE REMAINING FERRIC CHLORIDE.  AFTER SECURING THE DAMAGED DRUM, MR. BARNES CONTACTED PAUL ODONNELL (HB-BOM)TO INFORM OF THE SITUATION.  MR. ODONNELL CONTACTED THE FACILITY OPERATIONS MANAGER STEVEN TAYVINSKY TO OBTAIN INCIDENT DETAILS AND ESTABLISH FURTHER ACTIONS NEEDED.  MR. ODONNELL CONFIRMED THE SPILL WAS LESS THEN THE RQ (1000#) AND THE SPILL DID NOT GO OFF SITE.  AT THIS TIME MR. ODONNELL CONTACTED A CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR (EP&S) TO RESPOND TO THE SITE AND REMOVE THE EXPOSED GRAVEL.  DURING THE INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE DRIVE HAD ALL FOUR DRUMS RESTING ON THE EDGE OF THE LIFTGATE.  THIS IS DUE TO THE TOPOGRAPHY OF THE DELIVERY.  THE DELIVERY VEHICLE HAS TO SIT ON AN INCLINE, WHICH MAKES REMOVING THE DRUMS FORM THE LIFTGATE DIFFICULT.  MR BARNES STATED THAT IT TAKES TWO PEOPLE TO SAFELY REMOVE THE DRUM FROM THE GATE.  AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT THE CUSTOMER HAD NOT YET REACHED THE TRUCK TO ASSIST THE DRIVER.  IN AN ATTEMPT TO REMOVE A DRUM, A SECOND DRUM WAS PUSHED FROM THE GATE CAUSING THE SPILL.  JIM FLEISHER (HB-DISPATCHER) MADE A TRIP TO THE SITE ON THE DAY OF THE INCIDENT AND CONFIRMED THE ACCESS TO THE DELIVER SITE WAS LESS THAN IDEAL.  MR. FLEISHER ALSO AGREES IT WOULD TAKE TWO PEOPLE TO SAFELY REMOVE THE DRUMS AND TAKE THEM TO THE WWTP. DURING THE INVESTIGATION AN ADDITIONAL DRIVER (TOM LINGLE) WAS INTERVIEWED THAT HAD DELIVER TO THE SITE.  MR. LINGLE CONFIRMED THAT HE HAS THE SAME DIFFICULTIES DELIVERING AT THIS SITE.  MR. LINGLE ALSO STATED THAT AT ONE TIME THE COMPANY WAS ABLE TO MAKE THE DELIVERY TO A LOADING DOCK APPROXIMATELY 60 YARDS FROM THE WWTP.

A TRAIN CONDUCTOR REPORTED AN AMMONIA ODOR COMING FROM A TANK CAR, TJRX20465, RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED, ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, ON AN ADJACENT TRACK IN CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN THOMASVILLE, GA.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INSPECT THE CAR AND TO REPAIR THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  THE CONTRACTOR DISCOVERED THAT THE SAMPLE VALVE INSIDE THE DOME WAS BEND AND CRACKED AT THE BASE WHERE THE PIPE WAS CONNECTED TO THE PRESSURE PLATE.  A MIDLAND KIT WAS PLACED OVER THE VALVE TO STOP THE LEAK.  THE SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE WERE NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  TANNER INDUSTRIES ARRANGED TO BRING IN A TANKER LOAD OF WATER TO BLOW THE PRESSURE OFF THE TANK CAR.  CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED LATER IN THE EVENING THAT THE CONDUCTOR WHO REPORTED THE LEAK, MR CG LOWERY, HAD COMPLAINED OF WATERING EYES FORM THE VAPORS AND REQUESTED TO BE TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL FOR EXAMINATION.  THE HOSPITAL CONDUCTED A BLOOD GAS TEST ON MR LOWERY AND FOUND NO EVIDENCE OF AMMONIA IN HIS BLOOD.  MR LOWEREY WAS RELEASED.  ON 06-28-04 THE PRESSURE ON TJRX20465 WAS REDUCED TO ATMOSPHERE BY BLOWING THE VAPORS OFF INTO A WATER BATH.  THE SAMPLE LINE WAS REMOVED AND THE ORIFICE IN THE PRESSURE PLATE WAS PLUGGED WITH A PIPE PLUG.  THE CAR WAS TAGGED FOR HOME SHOP FOR REPAIRS.

column168: GEOFFREY REEDER, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL SITE REMEDIATION, WAS NOTIFIED OF A LEAKING TANK CAR AT ABOUT 7 PM.  INITIAL REPORTS INDICATED THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET.  A LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, EAGLE EMERGENCY SERVICES, WAS CONTACTED AND ASKED TO RESPOND.  UPON ARRIVAL, EAGLE REPRESENTATIVES ADVISED THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR, FROM UNDER THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER.  REEDER INSTRUCTED EAGLE TO OPEN THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AND INSPECT THE VALVES.  EAGLE REMOVED AN ARCHER DANIELS MIDLAND SEAL AND FOUND THE LEAK WAS COMING THROUGH THE PACKING AROUND THE STEM OF THE LIQUID VALVE.  REEDER ADVISED THEM TO REMOVE THE PLUG FROM THE AIR LINE AND CAREFULLY OPEN THE AIR VALVE TO RELIEVE PRESSURE ON THE CAR AND STOP THE RELEASE.  UPON DOING SO, THE RELEASE STOPPED.  REEDER THEN DIRECTED EAGLE TO EXAMINE THE PACKING.  THE PACKING GLAND NUT WAS LOOSE.  EAGLE PERSONNEL TIGHTENED THE PACKING GLAND NUT.  THE HOUSING WAS RESEALED WITH CTS SEAL 000294.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.  CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.

column168: ON THE MORNING OF JUNE 28, 2004 AT APPROX. 10:20 OTL/UPT'S DRIVER BA THIEN MAI WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON I-435 AND WAS TAKING THE I-70 WEST EXIT.  THE ON RAMP TO I-70 WEST IS POSTED AT 30 MPH.  MR. BA CLAIMS ANOTHER VEHICLE CUT HIM OFF CAUSING HIM TO ABRUPTLY APPLY HIS BRAKES AND LOOSE CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE.  THE TRACTOR-TRAILER ROLLED ON IT'S LEFT SIDE SKIDDING FOR APPROX. 47 YARDS, COMING TO REST BLOCKING TWO LANES OF FOUR LANES ON I-70.  THE TRAILER RECEIVED THREE SMALL HOLES AS A RESULT OF THE KIDDING. (EACH BEING APPROX. 6")  THE HOLES RESULTED IN THE LOSS OF 7500 GALS OF JP8 JET FUEL. THE FUEL POOLED IN TWO AREAS, HOWEVER BECAUSE OF TORRENTIAL RAINS PRIOR TO THE INCIDENT THE FUEL MADE IT'S WAY TO A CULVERT AND FOLLOWED A DITCH TO A SMALL STEAM BEFORE IT WAS CONTAINED. (APPROX. 3 MILES)  THE DRIVE (MR. BA) REPORTED ONLY MINOR INJURIES TO HIS HEAD AND WAS SEEN AT A LOCAL CLINIC. MR. BA WAS RELEASED AND INSTRUCTED TO RETURN TO THE CLINIC FOR FOLLOW-UP. ACTIONS TAKEN AT TIME DISCOVERED:  ON THE MORNING OF JUNE, 28, 2004 AT APPROX. 10:45 THE KANSAS HIGHWAY PATROL CONTACTED OTL/UPT'S WICHITA CSC(CUSTOMER SERVICE CENTER) STATING OTL/UPT HAD A ROLLOVER.  THE CSC MANAGER (RUSS SHINERT) IMMEDIATELY CALLED ME (JAMES SMITH, DIRECTOR OF SAFETY).  RUSS STATED THAT BA MAI WAS IN KANSAS CITY AND HAD ROLLED THE TRUCK ON A RAMP AND THAT THE TRAILER WAS LEAKING JET FUEL.  RUSS ALSO STATED THE DRIVER WAS NOT SERIOUSLY HURT AND THAT NO OTHER CARS WERE INVOLVED.  I ASKED IF THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED, RUSS SAID NO AND THAT THE HIGHWAY PATROL HAD ALREADY CALLED EMERGENCY CREWS.  I IMMEDIATELY CALLED THE DRIVER BA MAI TO ASK IF HE WAS ALRIGHT AND IF HE COULD CONTAIN THE SPILL.  BA MAI STATED THE LEAKS WERE TO BAD AND HE COULD NOT STOP THEM.  AT THIS TIME HAZ-MAT ONE OUT OF OLATHE, KANSAS (913-782-5151) WAS CALLED IN FOR CLEAN UP.  HAZ-MAT ONE PLACED SEVERAL DIKES, DAMS AND BOOMS AND THE EPA ALSO PUT A DAM IN.  ALL THESE MEASURES WERE TAKEN TO PREVENT THE FUEL FROM SPREADING.  THE KANASAS HIGHWAY PATROL CLOSED PART OF I-70 UNTIL THE TRUCK AND TRAILER COULD BE REMOVED. (APPROX. 17:30) THE RAMP REMAINED CLOSED UNTIL 07:00 THE NEXT MORNING TO EXPEDITE THE REMOVAL OF CONTAMINATED SOIL. OTL/UPT, HAZ-MAT ONE, KANSAS DEPT OF HEALTH & ENVIRONMENT, THE EPA AND ALL LOCAL & STATE EMERGENCY PERSONAL WORKED TOGETHER TO ENSURE A PROMPT AND ENVIRONMENTALLY FRIENDLY CLEAN-UP.

column168: JIM SHEENY, CHIEF CLERK, REPORTED CONTAINER CSXU 681138, WAS LEAKING SEVERAL DROPS OF AN UNKNOWN LIQUID, WHILE BEING OFF LOADED FROM THE RAIL CAR.  THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE HAZMAT CONTAINMENT AREA AT THE CITY OF INDUSTRY INTERMODAL YARD.  DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  MANAGER COOPER INSPECTED THE CONTAINER AND FOUND THE CONTENTS TO BE 64 FIFTY FIVE GALLON POLY DRUMS, AND APPROXIMATELY ONE THIRD OF THE DRUMS WERE DISTRESSED FROM WHAT APPEARED TO BE PRESSURE BUILD UP.  MANAGER COOPER STATED THERE WAS NO ACTIVE LEAK, HOWEVER, IT APPEARED THE PRODUCT HAD EXPANDED INSIDE THE DRUMS AND LEAKED SEVERAL GALLONS WHILE IN TRANSIT, AS EVIDENCED BY THE DRIED PRODUCT TRAIL DOWN THE LOWER BOTTOM OF THE CONTAINER.  THE ACTUAL SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED THE FOLLOWING MORNING.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO VENT EACH OF THE DRUMS TO RELIEVE THE INTERNAL PRESSURE.  ONCE THE DRUMS WERE VENTED, THEY WERE REMOVED AND INSPECTED.  ONE DRUM WAS LOCATED IN THE LEFT FRONT CORNER OF THE CONTAINER THAT HAD BEEN IMPACTED BY A BOWED OUT SIDEWALL SCUFF PLATE. THE PLATE HAD PULLED LOOSE FROM THE WALL AND RUBBED AGAINST THE SIDEWALL OF THE POLY DRUM, EVENTUALLY WEARING THROUGH AND CAUSING A RELEASE OF PRODUCT. IT APPEARED THE CONTAINER WAS DEFECTIVE AT THE TIME OF LOADING, AS THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE THAT THE PLATE SUSTAINED ANY DAMAGE FROM THE DRUMS TO CAUSE THE BOWING OF THE METAL.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM FOR SECUREMENT.  A SECOND DRUM IN THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER HAD A SMALL CRACK IN THE SIDEWALL DIRECTLY BELOW THE TOP CHIME.  IT APPEARS THIS CRACK DEVELOPED AS THE POLY DRUM WAS EXPANDING DUE TO THE INTERNAL PRESSURE BUILD UP.  THIS DRUM WAS ALSO PATCHED AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM FOR SECUREMENT.  THE COMBINATION KNEE BRACE AND END GATE SECUREMENT APPEARED TO BE ADEQUATE, HOWEVER, DID NOT MEET THE AAR-BOE 6C REQUIREMENTS. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO TRANSFER THE LADING INTO CONTAINER CSXU 681319. THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE LOADED, ALONG WITH THE 2 SALVAGE DRUMS, THEN BLOCKED AND BRACED FOR OVER THE ROAD DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE.

column168: This letter is a written report of the above referenced spill episode as required by the Polyglass Stormwater Pollution Prevention and Contingency Plan (Stormwater Permit #PAR322204). On June 9, 2004 between 1:00 AM and 2:00 AM, a trucker hooked his flexible hose from his truck to one of the 2 large asphalt storage tanks that is located outside the rear of the plant. The trucker claims that he observed proper filling procedures for 5 to 10 minutes before he violated the Polyglass required protocol by leaving the area, and abandoning proper surveillance. Approximately 5,800 gallons of asphalt were spilled from the trucker’s flexible pipe onto the surrounding asphalt pavement. The spill flowed down gradient in a 40’ wide path down to the fence line and beyond. The spill continued under the railroad tracks and through a corrugated pipe, covering a total running length of 150 feet. The spill extended 30 feet beyond the property line onto adjacent Cando-owned property before coming to a rest. No water was flowing in the drainage channel at the time of the incident nor did the spilled material reach any bodies of water.    At approximately 2:00 AM, the trucker became aware of his spill and he phoned his office supervisor, Justin Barletta, who immediately drove from the Hazleton area to the site. Mr. Barletta had difficulty assessing the extent of the spill because he arrived when it was still dark. Later, Mr. Barletta told Gary Snook of Polyglass that he optimistically thought the spill was rather small, and he thought his l.rucker had deposited most of the load into the large storage tank. At that point, they decided to wait for the mornirg when Gary Snook, the Plant Manager, would arrive, so they could discuss the episode with him.    Upon Gary’s arrival, he toured the area of concern with Mr. Barletta, and they realized the etent of the spill was much larger than thought. As they walked the spill area, they discovered a deer in the downstream field that had been killed by the asphalt.    Mr. Barletta then called his company’s (TBT Trucking, Hazieton, PA) spill response team (Datom), and they were said to be leaving their Dunmore office to arrive on-site at 9:30 AM. Gary Snook called CAG to implement the PPC Plan and to have CAG notify all appropriate regulatory authorities. CAG verified the Polyglass PPC Plan is current, and Joe Mazzoni of CAG began following the plan steps to notify authorities (DEP — Len Insalaco; and the National Response Center). Telephone notifications were made to both agencies within 1 hour, and before 9:30 AM.    By 9:30 AM, Joe Mazzoni left for Polyglass Hazieton to meet with DEP and the trucker’s spill team. Joe Mazzoni arrived onsite at 10:30am and observed the spill area to adequately describe the extent of the spill in this Incident Report. Joe Mazzoni met with Jonathan Ulanoski of PADEP and Tom Jimmy of Datom to discuss the extent and appropriate cleanup measures. On June 9, 2004, Datorn initiated spill cleanup measure
column169: To prevent future possible occurrences, Gary Snook said he would begin consideration of various plans to prevent any possible release beyond the property line in the future. Presently, he is considering an earth berm along the rear property line that will allow stormwater absorption in the grassy areas, yet prevent any possible future asphalt spills from leaving the property.
